We’re thrilled with the response to the Plainfield Schools lunch program during this difficult time. In fact, our numbers continue to grow which makes us very happy.

One thing we’d like to clarify, however: we’re doing this because we want to be sure Plainfield children don’t go hungry amidst all the other challenges brought about by COVID-19. It has nothing to do with federal funding.

Feeding children is what it’s all about, and with that in mind, our routes will continue over Spring Break.

post_text: Thank you, Town of Plainfield Indiana, for this excellent explanation of what the Governor's Executive Order does and does not mean.
shared_text:
Town of Plainfield - Government
March 24 at 8:07 PM ·

Gov. Eric Holcomb's Stay-at-Home Order goes into effect at 11:59 this evening.

In addition to Governor Holcomb’s directive to end unnecessary travel and to say at home, all Plainfield playgrounds, parks restroom facilities and all other gathering facilities (shelters and gazebos) have been closed and restricted from use.

While outdoor recreation is not prohibited, please continue to practice social distancing while out on walks or other outdoor activities, maintaining at least 6 feet from other neighbors and their pets.

As a reminder, the Town of Plainfield launched a Resident Assistance Program to help deliver essentials to high-risk populations contact us via email (residentassistance@townofplainfield.com) or phone (317-839-2561 ext. 1).

Finally, if you think you have been exposed to COVID-19 and develop a fever and symptoms of respiratory illness, such as cough or difficulty breathing, the CDC advises you to call your medical provider immediately. Hendricks Regional Health has created a 24/7 hotline for over-the-phone screenings (317) 520-5500.

Plainfield Community School Corporation added 9 new photos — at Eagle Creek Park - Indy Parks and Recreation.

Most of these photos are from before or after today's Polar Plunge which supports Special Olympics Indiana, and their tagline, "Freezin' for a Reason" was incredibly poignant on this COLD morning. Yes, the wind was brisk and the wind chill was around 22 degrees, but Plainfield was represented by eight district administrators, several teachers, 30 high school students who "took the plunge," and two more classrooms of students who cheered on their friends. #powerful #QuakerFaces

post_text: Final update from today's Girls State Swim&Dive finals. As written by the PHS AD, "Great day for this crew! @PHS_swimdive and @SwimPCA are building something special. Exceptionally proud of all the hard work from our swimmers, divers, and coaches. Even better days ahead. A special thank you to our only senior, Maggie McGuire. What a great career!" Junior Elle Gilkerson finished 16th in the State in the 100 Breaststroke. And the PHS 200 Free Relay had a great race to finish 14th in the State!

post_text: With his mother's permission, I am so excited to share this awesome stop-motion animation with you! For those in Indiana, #RileyDanceMarathon has grown to become a statewide, community-wide effort. Its origins come from college campuses, and now high schools are part of the fun. Plainfield High School students enthusiastically took on this event several years ago, and I continue to be impressed with their passion #4TK (For The Kids). Nolan and his friends are now taking it to yet another level. Riley Children's Foundation
shared_text:
Andrea Goss Birke
February 4 at 11:56 PM ·

My name is Nolan Birke, I am 12 years old and I've been a Riley kid since I was born. It would mean a lot to me if you would make a donation to support the world's first Dance Marathon created with toys!

I created a video and fundraiser in honor of my friend Jack Moon, who was recently diagnosed with cancer. I am hoping to raise $2,500 for Riley Hospital for Children, the hospital that helped both Jack and me.

I was born with clubfoot and needed complicated surgeries on my feet and legs. My Riley surgeons did such a great job that today I am a competitive track and cross country runner for my school teams! My dad also works for Riley Children's Foundation so our whole family gets to see how donations are used to help Riley kids like me every day.

I hope you enjoy watching the Toy Dance Marathon video. My dad and I worked together to create the stop-action animation video and we had a lot of fun! Please help us by donating at https://bit.ly/2v4qpWN.

post_text:
Looking for a special but not-over-the-top expensive dinner for Valentine's Day? We suggest the @Area31 Culinary Arts program!

This event will take place on Friday, February 14, 2020, with two dinner seatings available. One at 5:30pm and another at 7:00p.m.

Tickets are $60 and include a 3 course meal for 2 as well as a bouquet of flowers.

**You must pay in advance to reserve your table. No Refunds. We accept cash, checks, Visa or MasterCard.**

Contact Area31's Liz Silence at (317)988-7223 to make your reservation.
